\begin{align*}
\prod_{n=0}^{\infty} 2^{k \cdot 2^{-n}}.
\end{align*}
Notice that the powers of 2 are the same, and we can invoke the sum rule for exponents:
\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} k \cdot 2^{-n} = k \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} 2^{-n}.
\end{align*}
Since this is a geometric series with ratio $1/2$, we see that the sum is $2k$. Hence, our product can be written as
\begin{align*}
\prod_{n=0}^{\infty} 2^{k \cdot 2^{-n}} &=2^{2k} \\
&= 2^{2(\frac{1}{3})} \\
&= \boxed{\sqrt[3]{4}}.
\end{align*}
